The start symbol S can expand only in two ways:

1. S → NT54 NT0  
2. S → NT57 NT37  

Examine each option against the terminals that must appear in any derivation:

────────────────────────────
Option 2: S → NT57 NT37
────────────────────────────
NT37’s only rule is NT37 → NT25 NT5, and NT5 → ‘t9’.  
Therefore every sentence derived with this option must contain the
terminal t9.  
The given string contains no t9 at all, so this option is impossible.

────────────────────────────
Option 1: S → NT54 NT0
────────────────────────────
Whatever NT0 produces has to be the final part of the string.

The rules for NT0 are

• NT0 → ‘t4’  
• NT0 → ‘t3’  
• NT0 → NT44 NT5          (ends with the terminal t9)  
• NT0 → NT58 NT51         (NT51 produces either ‘t1’ or NT40 NT18; neither
                           NT18 nor any of its descendants can yield t6)

Hence every derivation of NT0 ends with one of the terminals
t4, t3, or t9 – never with t6.

Because the given string ends with t6, no derivation using
S → NT54 NT0 can match it.

────────────────────────────
Conclusion
────────────────────────────
Both possible first–level derivations from S are ruled out, so the grammar
cannot generate the provided string.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT54 NT0  
   – The final token of the whole string must come from NT0.  
   – Every derivation of NT0 ends with either  
     • a terminal t4 or t3 (via NT0 → 't4' / 't3'),  
     • a token produced by NT18 (through NT0 → NT58 NT51 → … → NT18),  
     • or the terminal t9 (via NT0 → NT44 NT5 with NT5 → 't9').  
   – NT18 can finish only with t4, t7, t1 or t3.  
   – Thus NT0 can end only with t3, t4 or t9 – never with t2.  
   – Because the given string ends with t2, this expansion of S is impossible.

2. S → NT57 NT37  
   – NT37 is fixed: NT37 → NT25 NT5 and therefore produces exactly two tokens, the second of which is always t9 (since NT5 → 't9').  
   – Hence any string derived through this branch must end in “… tₓ t9”.  
   – The given string ends with “… t9 t2”, not “… tₓ t9”, so this branch is also impossible.

Since neither of the only two possible top-level derivations for S can yield a string whose last symbols match the required “… t9 t2”, the grammar cannot generate the provided 38-token string.
